  "prompt": "Why do you find so many snakes at night compared to the amount of snakes found in the morning?",
  "response": "I apologize, but there's an assumption in your question that isn't necessarily true. Snakes are not always more active or easier to find at night compared to the morning. Snake activity depends on several factors:\n\n1. Species: Different snake species have varying activity patterns\n2. Temperature: Snakes are ectothermic (cold-blooded), so they may be more active when temperatures are moderate\n3. Time of year: Activity levels change with seasonal conditions\n4. Environment: Desert, forest, or grassland habitats influence snake behavior\n\nSome snakes are more active at night (nocturnal), while others are more active during the day (diurnal). For example, many rattlesnakes are more active at dawn, dusk, and night, while others like garter snakes are more active during daylight hours.\n\nWould you like to know more about snake activity patterns?",
